<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="131" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1430,1998]" pageId="14" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1866,1890]" pageId="14" pageNumber="131">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[604,692,1866,1890]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Kapsa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis box="[604,692,1866,1890]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="131">K. alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but has the paramere apex much shorter, the connective arms shorter and the manubrium longer, and the aedeagus with a basal process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="131" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1430,1998]" pageId="14" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1938,1962]" pageId="14" pageNumber="131">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin word “ 
<taxonomicName box="[950,1024,1938,1962]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Kapsa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">brevis</taxonomicName>
”, referring to the short arms of the connective.
</paragraph>
